<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: POMONA; POLICE OFFICE OPENS DOWNTOWN ON 'ANTIQUE ROW' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city's newest police office is nestled between stores that tout old 
political buttons, decades-old lamps and other antique wares. In an office 
complete with a vintage radio, the Pomona Police Department opened its fifth 
community service center earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
 This center, at 106 S. Locust St. in the "antique row" district of the 
downtown area, is being funded by the Pomona Central Business District. 
</P>
<P>
 Area business owners are providing the rent money for their new neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
 "It gives you a more secure feeling," said Mike Hunter, who along with wife 
Debi runs Hunter's Collectibles next door to the police center. 
</P>
<P>
 The center will be the home of the department's graffiti/abatement coordinator 
and the department's new STOP (Stop Trouble Occurring in Pomona) team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
