<DOCID> 056136 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
June 30, 1994, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
South Bay; Part J; Page 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
114 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY HALL; REDONDO BEACH; BUDGET ALLOWS FOR 2 ADDITIONAL FIREFIGHTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY GUTHRIE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ending an attrition program that cut 77 positions in three years, the Redondo 
Beach City Council added two firefighting positions to the city's staff 
Tuesday.The decision came as part of the approval of the city's budget for 
fiscal year 1994-95. 
</P>
<P>
 The city's $63-million budget also adds two public works employees and $55,000 
for incentives, bonuses and other compensation. 
</P>
<P>
 A controversial plan to charge residents and businesses a monthly fee to fund 
$16 million in maintenance and repairs to the city's sewer system was vetoed by 
Mayor Brad Parton earlier this month, but the city did approve $2 million to 
start some of those projects under the new budget. MARY GUTHRIE 
</P>
</TEXT>
