<TEXT>
<P>
 ON TARGET: When local employment consultant Ruth Fassets calls companies about 
hiring the disabled, she says, "They usually talk about cutbacks or needing a 
fast worker." Officials at Target in Irvine were different, she notes: "They 
not only were enthusiastic, they set up working hours for one to accommodate 
his bus schedule." . . . . Result: the Irvine store will be honored today by 
the Orange County Employment Advocacy Network for "best innovation" in 
employing the disabled. 
</P>
<P>
 GOOD POET SOCIETY: Comedy skits and lively Latino music will fill the air at 
La Casa Garia restaurant in Anaheim tonight. But its purpose is a serious one. 
. . . Edelmira Marin, 17, was just a few steps from her home in La Habra when 
she was fatally struck by a car two months ago. Her family, struggling 
financially, is still trying to pay off her funeral expenses. The Chicano Poet 
Society put together tonight's fund-raiser to help them. 
</P>
<P>
 OPRY STEPS: Ed Applegate of Laguna Hills jokes that he goes country dancing 
"about every night." It's paying off. . . . He and dance partner Tina Bright of 
Costa Mesa are Southern California winners of a free trip to Nashville, Tenn. 
They'll be finalists in the "Best Two-Stepping Couple in America" contest at 
Opryland. Bright and Applegate say they hadn't expected to win -- other couples 
had impressive, preset routines. "We just decided to have fun, and we clicked," 
Applegate says. "The judges liked that." 
</P>
<P>
 NOT SO FUNNY? It was a comedy team not meant to be. When John Wayne Bobbitt 
announced he wanted to try comedy, comedian Todd Glass, currently performing at 
the Brea Improv, was interested. Bobbitt gained notoriety after his wife, 
citing his physical abuse, cut off his penis. . . . "We wanted to do something 
clever with it; he would draw people," says Glass. Problem is, Bobbitt didn't 
want to be part of Glass' act, and negotiations broke down. Just as well, says 
Glass: "Comedy and wife abuse just don't go together." 
</P>
