<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OJAI; CITY COUNCIL VOTES TO RAISE MOTEL BED TAX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JASON GRANT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Ojai City Council has voted to increase its resort and motel bed tax from 
8% to 10% in a controversial move aimed at paying for a steep hike in the cost 
of law enforcement. 
</P>
<P>
 The council approved the higher tax Tuesday evening as it approved a 
$6.39-million budget for the fiscal year beginning Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Ojai motel and resort owners were granted one concession by the council, a 
30-day delay before collections of the new tax begin in August. 
</P>
<P>
 Upset business owners during Tuesday's public hearing argued for at least a 
90-day reprieve. Owners said they expect to have to absorb increased costs to 
customers who have made advanced reservations at their lodges. They pleaded for 
time to print up new materials. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm disappointed," said Ben Larner, owner of Best Western Casa Ojai. "Thirty 
days will help, 90 days would be better." 
</P>
<P>
 The bed tax increase was expected to bring $170,000 to the city, more than 
covering a projected $130,000 jump in law enforcement costs. It has not been 
calculated how much revenue will be lost because of the 30-day delay. 
</P>
<P>
 Ten Ojai hotels will be affected by the tax increase, officials said, adding 
between $1.10 and $5 per day to bills. 
</P>
<P>
 The council at first split on delaying implementation of the bed tax. Two 
members backed a 90-day reprieve, but two others said the city could not afford 
the loss of any city revenue, especially since Ojai is planning costly 
litigation to challenge the Weldon Canyon Landfill initiative. JASON GRANT 
</P>
</TEXT>
