<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; NEW BUDGET MAKES ROOM FOR ROAD WORK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After dipping into its reserves to pay for repaving of city streets, the Simi 
Valley City Council has unanimously adopted a budget for the fiscal year that 
begins Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Saying street improvements are a top priority, the City Council agreed to take 
$237,900 out of the city's reserve fund to help cover the cost of a 
$1.78-million citywide road resurfacing project it had postponed earlier in the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 The road work, which includes stripping and repaving thoroughfares across the 
city that were damaged by rain or during the recent earthquake, is scheduled to 
begin in July. 
</P>
<P>
 The $28.5-million spending plan approved by the council represents an 8.7% 
increase from fiscal year 1993-94. 
</P>
<P>
 City Budget Director Ken Schechter said the increase was caused mainly by the 
cost of the road project and a drop in a surplus retirement revenue fund the 
city had relied on in past years to offset rising expenses. 
</P>
<P>
 "The overall budget increase is a little bit bigger than what you would 
normally see from one year to the next," Schechter said. "But the city is in 
good shape financially." SARA CATANIA 
</P>
