<P>
 Union Carbide Corp. Sells Smog Credits: The company's plant in Torrance became 
the first major participant in the state's controversial Regional Clean Air 
Incentives Market program, under which companies are given pollution credits 
that may be sold.State officials said the plant sold 3.4 million credits -- 
$1.2-million worth -- last week to Anchor Glass Container Corp., a private 
company in Huntington Park. A credit gives the owner the right to emit a pound 
of nitrogen oxide. The program, launched in October, aims to reduce total 
allowable emissions in coastal Southern California by 80% by the year 2010. An 
auction designed to handle high trading volume has twice been postponed for 
lack of demand. 
